change: An overnight curfew from 6 PM to 6 AM was enforced In Albania beginning from 16 March. Also outside of curfew times, people were generally only allowed outside for going to work or to make essential purchases in the “essential businesses” remaining open.
Curfew hours were extended to 18 hours a day. From 19 March, it was only allowed to be outside alone and with an important reason from 6 AM to 10 AM and from 4 PM to 6 PM.

From 23 March on, it was only allowed to be outside from 5 AM to 1 PM. From 1 PM to 5 AM, the only ones who were allowed to circulate were police and military (who were enforcing the measure), freight transport services, government service units, authorized media personnel, food delivery vehicles, and others with special authorization that needed to be applied for on a website. Even in an emergency situation, people needed to call the police before leaving their house. Anyone outside without a valid reason (e.g. just going for a walk) risked a fine. On Sundays, the strict curfew expanded over the entire day.

From 30 March on, the stay-at-home order was further strictened so that only one member per household could leave for essential purchases for one hour each day. Residents needed to apply for a permit to leave their homes for essential purposes.

From 13 April on, business hours were expanded to 5 AM to 5.30 PM, but only from Monday to Friday while on Saturdays everything stayed close from this day on. From the same day on, people were granted 90 minutes a day for essential shopping with permission.
On Sunday, 19 April, mothers with children up to 10 years old were allowed to go outside until 11 AM.
On 25 April, elderly citizens were allowed to exercise outside before 11 AM

Starting from 27 April, stay-at-home measures were gradually relaxed. Residents of 11 municipalities could move without authorisation with one more person between 9 AM and 5.30 PM. People were not allowed to drive out of these districts.  Retired people were allowed ouside in these cities from 6 AM to 8.30 AM as well. In the following weeks, these ""green zones"" have been expanded to cover further municipalities""
On the weekends 2/3 May and 9/10 May, senior citizens were allowed to go out before 10 AM and parents as well as children below 14 were allowed to go out from 11 AM to 5.30 PM.
On the weekends 2/3 May and 9/10 May, senior citizens were allowed to go out before 10 AM and parents as well as children below 14 were allowed to go out from 11 AM to 5.30 PM.

From 18 May on, there was no need for authorization of movements anymore in the entire country. Yet, in the red zones, there was still an overnight curfew after 9 PM. Movement in the green zones was unrestricted starting this day.
No stay-at-home order in place anymore
Since 15 October, it was mandatory to wear a face mask in all public places, open or closed.
From 11 November, people were not allowed to leave their houses between 10 PM and 6 AM unless they had a special permission for work or other ""important reasons"".
The curfew will continue indefinitely.
Curfew times were extended to 8.30 PM to 6 AM.
Curfew times changed to 10 PM to 6 AM
From 11 February, the curfew started at 8 PM
The curfew starts at 10 PM again. Masks still had to be worn everywhere.
Curfew hours are changed to 11 PM to 6 AM. Masks are no longer mandatory outside.

I have not found a stay-at-home order, but as it was loosened later, such a law was apparently in place. Most probably a stay-at-home order was included in the ban on all unssential activities that took effect on 17 March.

From 16 April, those who live in even-numbered homes were allowed to go out on even dates, while those who reside in odd-numbered homes on all other days. Houses without a number were allowed to go out on even dates if the name of occupants begins with A-M, and odd days if it starts with N-Z. But going out was only allowed for one hour a day. There were still strict regulations on times depending on who wanted to go out for which purpose: Running or walking fast could take place between 6 am and 9 am or from 6 pm to 9 pm. Andorrans could shop or stroll between 9 am and 11 am or between 2 pm and 7 pm. The time between 11 am and 2 pm was reserved for vulnerable and elderly populations to get out of the house. Movement was limited to a maximum of 2 km distance from the house.
From 13 May, the 2 km rule fell and further outdoor activities such as mountain hiking, cycling, and fishing were allowed
All stay-at-home requirements were lifted as of 1 June
A mask had to be worn everywhere in public with few exceptions (such as activities in nature with a minimum distance of 4 m toward others).

The municipalities Ischgl, Kappl, See, Galtur and St. Anton am Arlberg in Tyrol were quarantined. Foreign visitors were told to leave, but residents and Austrian guests were forced to stay. Several further municipalities have been put in quarantine in the subsequent days, for example several villages in the Arlberg region (ech, Warth,  Schrocken as well as Stuben in Klosterle municipality) from 17 March.

From 16 March, it was not allowed to enter public spaces unless for emergencies, caretaking of those in need of care, necessary purchases (i.e. groceries, medicine) and professional work. It was also allowed to enter public spaces alone, with members of the same household, or with pets if a distance of 1m was maintained to others. So technically it was not a stay-at-home order like in many other countries, but a ban on frequenting public space (which is equivalent in its implications). Yet, the wording of the order left room for interpretation and government officials declared that going for a walk would be allowed as well while some legal experts even interpreted the rule in a way that it is allowed to leave the house for any reason as long as distance to others is kept. The ban on entering public spaces was initially valid until 22 March, but ultimately, it was prolonged consecutively until 30 April.
On 14 July, the Austrian Constitutional Court ruled that the general ban on entering public spaces was not legal. The laws only permitted the government to ban the access to certain, defined areas, but did not give the government the right to impose a general ban on all public areas or a ban to leave the house. As a reaction to this judgement, the Austrian parliament passed a new pandemic law on 23 September that enabled general stay-at-home orders and mask mandates.

The county of Tyrol put all its municipalities on quarantine which included a stay-at-home order that was valid from 19 March, originally until 5 April, but later prolonged until 13 April. From the used data and sources, it seems that this additional rule had no effect on the freedom of movement of people inside their municipality when compared to the federal stay-at-home order. The main difference was that it was not allowed to leave the municipality of residence unless important reasons could be proven.
The quarantine in Tyrol ended with this day, but not everywhere. Some areas (St. Anton, Paznauntal, Solden) remain under quarantine.
The last municipalities in Tyrol were freed from quarantine.
The stay-at-home order was lifted taking effect on this date.
A curfew was set in place from 8 PM to 6 AM, but exceptions included being outside “for physical and mental recreation”.
The curfew was transformed into a general stay-at-home order, with many exceptions including being outside ""for physical and mental recreation""
From 7 December, the stay-at-home mandate was only valid for the night again, corresponding to a curfew from 8 PM to 6 AM with the exceptions as before.
The curfew was transformed into a general stay-at-home order again, with many exceptions including being outside ""for physical and mental recreation"" It was prolonged serveral times.
From 8 February, the stay-at-home mandate was only valid for the night again, corresponding to a curfew from 8 PM to 6 AM with the exceptions as before.
From 27 February, the municipality of Mayrhofen im Zillertal imposed a ban on leaving the municipality without a negative test. Several other municipalities followed over the subsequent weeks.

In three provinces (Wien, Niederosterreich, Burgenland) the lockdown was during the day again with the same exceptions as above. In Vienna (Wien), masks were made obligatory at several highly frequented places.
The stricter lockdown in Wien and Niederosterreich was lifted on this day after it was already lifted in Burgenland on 19 April.
The curfew in Austria ended.
The ban on leaving the municipality without a negative test ended in Pitztal and Umhausen. These were the last such regulations in effect in Austria.

There have never been any stay-at-home orders, curfews or outside mask mandates in Belarus. People were free to leave their house or even their place of residence. There also have been no ban on contacts.

A stay-at-home order was introduced. The law did not explicitly order citizens to stay home, but banned all gatherings as well as all “cultural, social, festive, folkloric, sportive, or recreative activities” as well as school trips and religious ceremonies. All activities limited to family were allowed and it was explicitly allowed to go for a walk with family members living in the same household and with one more person. It was also explicitly allowed to exercise outdoors with family members living in the same house or with always the same friend, maintaining a distance of 1.5 m. Indeed, physical outdoor activities have even been recommended and encouraged by the government. On the other hand, it was not allowed to rest in public.
Going for a walk or physical activity was allowed with two people from other households.
Now, leisure activities outside were allowed again, not only exercise.
In more and more ""busy streets"" across the country as well as dikes at the coast, it was made obligatory to wear masks.
In Antwerp, a night curfew was put in place between 11.30 PM and 6 AM.
Due to a heatwave, the Antwerp curfew was suspended
The curfew in Antwerp now spanned from 1.30 AM to 5 AM.
The Antwerp curfew was lifted.
In the province of Brabant Wallon, a night curfew from 1 AM to 6 AM was put in place from 13 October.
In the province Luxembourg, a night curfew from 1 AM to 6 AM was put in place from 14 October.
On 19 October, a nationwide curfew followed. Between midnight and 5 AM, it was not allowed to enter public space unless for non-postponable reasons such as commuting to work or medical emergencies.
Wallonia extended the curfew on the time from 10 PM until 6 AM on 24 October.
Brussels-Capital extended the curfew on the time from 10 PM until 6 AM on 26 October.
In some regions, the curfew was not enforced in the night from 24 December to 25 December due to Christmas traditions.
From 1 March 2021, the curfew was in place from midnight to 5AM in Wallonie and Flanders whereas in Brussels it remained to be from 10 PM to 6 AM.
The curfew ended. It was replaced with a ban on meeting with more than 3 persons between midnight and 5 AM.

Legislation can generally differ in the two semi-autonomous states Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina (FBIH) and Republic Srpska (RS). On 22 March both regions introduced a stay-at-home order for seniors over the age of 65. In the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, minors under 18 were also obliged to stay home. The only exceptions were for minors in their parents car or for elderly people few hours on certain days to pick up their pensions. For everyone below 65 (in Srpska) or between 18 and 64 (in the Federation), a night curfew was announced. In the Federation, the curfew initially lasted from 6 PM to 5 AM, in the RS from 8 PM to 5 AM. In Brcko district, the curfew spanned from 9 PM to 5 AM.
Since 29 March, In the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, masks had to be worn generally in public. Curfew times changed to 8 PM to 5 AM.
In the Republic Srpska, people over 65 were allowed to be outside on Tuesdays and Fridays from 7 AM to 10 AM  from 31 March.
In RS, citizens were requested not to move away from their place of residence between Saturday 12 AM and Sunday 6 PM.
In FBIH, people over 65 were allowed to be outside as of 6 April from 8-12 AM.
In FBIH, in the cantons most hit by the outbreak, citizens were restricted from moving outside their place of residence.
Since 11 April, it was mandatory to wear a mask in the Republic Srpska as well.
On 22 April, the Constitutional Court ruled that the restrictions on elderly and minors were discriminatory and disproportionate.
The ban on leaving the municipality in FBIH was discontinued. I found no information when the respective weekend ban ended in the RS..

As of 24 April, in the FBIH, minors could leave their homes on Tuesdays, Thursdays, and Saturdays between 2 PM and 8 PM. Elderly (above 65) could leave their homes on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays between the hours of 0900-1300. The curfew was ended.

change: On 14 May, restriction of movement for both minors and the elderly were abolished in both FBIH and RS. As the curfew had already been abolished on 24 April, freedom of movement was restored for the entire population in FBIH. In the RS, the curfew from 10 PM to 5 AM remained in place
The curfew in RS was discontinued
In FBIH, wearing masks was not longer mandatory in open spaces with 2m distance to others
In RS, wearing masks was not longer mandatory in open spaces.
Wearing masks was made mandatory in open spaces in Sarajevo Canton
In RS, wearing masks was made mandatory in open spaces.
In FBIH, wearing masks was made obligatory in open spaces no matter the distance.
In FBIH, a curfew was set in place from 11 PM to 5 AM.
In the Sarajevo County, the curfew was extended to 9 PM to 5 AM

Apparently, masks have not been mandatory everywhere in the country irrespective of distance. This can be seen from Brcko district making them mandatory outdoors for groups of two persons or more. They do not seem to be mandatory everywhere in the RS either, but I found no news when this requirement was dropped.
In the city of Banja Luka, masks were no longer mandatory outdoors. This means they have not been mandatory in the RS at that point, but I couldn not find when the RS dropped the mandate yet.
In FBIH, wearing a mask was no longer mandatory in open spaces if a distance of 2m can be kept.
The curfew was abolished in West Herzegovina canton.
Curfew hours were reduced to 11 PM to 5 AM in FBIH.
The curfew in FBIH was lifted. Facemasks remain mandatory outdoors when a distance of 2m cannot be kept.

The town Bansko was put under quarantine until 31 March. It was not just prohibited to enter or leave the municipality, but also within Bansko, people were only allowed out for food and drug delivery or emergencies.
On 18 March, the town Kozloduy introduced a 10 PM to 6 AM curfew with the only reasons for leaving their house at this time being emergencies or work. (end date unknown!)
It was made mandatory to wear masks everywhere in public.
The Bansko quarantine ended. After just one day, the general mask mandate was overturned again. On the same day, the Stara Zagora province announced a curfew from 9 PM to 5 AM (end date unknown!)
It was made mandatory to wear masks everywhere in public again.
The town Panicherevo was put under quarantine with a local stay-at-home order until 28 April.
Masks were not required outdoors anymore. (according to Wikipedia this is from 1 May!)
The Panicherevo quarantine presumably ended.
It was announced to make masks mandatory outdoors. But ultimately mask wearing was only made mandatory where people congegrate and it is not possible to keep 1,5 m distance.
In Kyustendil district, it was made mandatory to wear masks outside, not only in crowded areas as elsewhere.
The temporary extra-strict mask mandate in Kyutendil ended, or at least it was planned to end by this date, I found no report that said that it actually ended.

From 23 March, Croatians were not allowed to leave their place of residence. Exceptions were for indispensable labour (e.g. in transport, health sector, or journalists) and “vital family reasons”. There is no information that people needed specific reasons to circulate within their place of residence.
The ban on leaving the municipality ended.
Authorities in the city of Zagreb announced making wearing masks obligatory outdoors, but the mayor turned over that decision later on the same day, so the mask mandate never took effect.

From 24 March, initially until 13 April, all movement was prohibited except for work-related reasons, the supply of basic necessities if shipping is not possible, visiting a doctor or pharmacy, for bank services if electronic transactions are not possible, for helping others in need of assistance, family ceremonies including first and second degree relatives such as funerals, weddings, and christenings, not exceeding ten people. It was also allowed to circulate for the purpose of physical exercise or for the needs of a pet, provided that there are not more than two people and they remain limited in areas adjacent to their residence. Everyone had to carry an ID and a proof for the purpose of their movement. The following places were closed:  parks, playgrounds, open-air sport locations, public gathering areas, such as squares, excursion sites, beaches and marinas
Among other changes, from this day on, it was only allowed to leave the house once a day. Furthermore, all movement between 9 PM and 6 AM was prohibited.
The lockdown ended on this date.
Wearing masks was made mandatory outdoors as well. Furthermore, a curfew from 11 PM to 5 AM was set in place in Limassol and Paphos.

As it had been the case before in Limassol and Paphos, from this day, a curfew was in place for the entire country. Between 11 PM and 5 AM people were only allowed outside for work purposes or emergencies. The curfew was extended for Limassol and Paphos from 12 November. For Christmas and New Years' Eve the curfew hours were slightly adapted.
From 10 January 2021, the curfew began at 9 PM.
Any movement of citizens was just allowed twice a day for a limited time and after sending a text message.
From 16 March, the curfew began at 11 PM again. It seems to have been changed several times between 9 PM and 11 PM.
From 30 March, the per day permissible number of text messages for movement purposes was increased to three on Saturdays and Sundays. It stayed two for weekdays.
As of 26 April, the curfew was from 9 PM to 5 AM. People were only allowed to go out once a day instead of twice, after requesting a permit per text message.
It was no longer necessary to get an approvement through text message in order to go out. People were free to leave home during the day, but they had to stay home between 11 PM and 5 AM.
As of 17 May, the curfew is postponed to start at midnight.
The curfew was ended.
A stay-at-home order was passed. Aside from buying essential goods and going to work or to the doctor, people were also allowed to go for a short walk e.g. in a park.
Wearing masks was now mandatory everywhere in public.
The stay-at-home order was lifted after a court found it to be unlawful due to formal reasons.
Masks don't have to be worn outside when maintaining a 2m distance to others. On 15 June, the 2m rule was also abolished.
People were obliged to stay home again (exemptions applied for travels to/from a job, basic grocery shopping, visits to close relatives, and stays in parks and nature and travel to/from it)
From 9 PM to 5 AM exemptions to go out became stricter, i.e. just going to work or emergencies.
From 23 November on, the curfew began later, at 11 PM.
The curfew and movement restrictions were abolished
A night curfew from 11 PM to 5 AM was imposed again. From 27 Devember, curfew time was changed to 9 PM to 5 AM.
Entry and exit from/to three districts (Trutnov, Chomutov and Sokolov) was banned and at the same time, it was mandatory to wear FFP 2 masks everywhere in these districts.
In all places, with a high concentration of people, an FFP 2 mask had to be worn from this day. In all other places (at least all urban places) a medical mask or an FFP 2 mask had to be worn.

From 1 March, people were not allowed to enter or exit their district of residence unless they had a valid reason, e.g. going to work. For sport and recreation, people even had to stay within the borders of their village of residence, but this has been widened to the entire district of residence on 22 March.
The curfew as well as the restriction on leaving the district of residence were lifted. A general mask mandate remained in place.
The outside mask mandate was abolished as long as a distance of 2m can be kept to other people.
There have never been any stay-at-home orders, curfews or outside mask mandates in Denmark. People were free to leave their house or even their place of residence.
Under the strictest restrictions during the first wave, gatherings of more than 10 persons were banned.
The general ban on assemblies was reduced on ten persons again.
The general ban on assemblies was reduced to five persons, the strictest thus far.
The limit for private gatherings was raised to 10 persons again.

The number of persons allowed for outdoor gatherings was raised from 10 to 50 persons and for indoor gatherings from 5 to 10. I will not report further opening steps as these measures already do not fall in what my project covers but I want to give an insight to the strictest restrictions that had been in place in every country.

Only permanent residents of Estonia's western islands of Hiiumaa, Kihnu, Muhu, Ruhnu, Saarema and Vormsi were permitted to access the islands. They were not allowed to leave their place of residence unless for a justified reason.

On the islands of Saaremaa and Muhu people had to stay at home. ""It is allowed to go to the grocery store, the pharmacy and the doctor. It is only allowed to go to work if it is not possible to do distance work. It is allowed to take children to the kindergarten and bring them home from there. If needed, it is allowed to go to take care of the elderly, the disabled and those in need of help, in that case personal protective equipment must definitely be used. It is allowed to go for a walk or a workout with family or one other person. Pets can be taken out and to the veterinarian. It is allowed to move in your own garden or on your own property, to do forestry or farm work at home, to fish, to do gardening. It is allowed to go to the post office or a parcel terminal. A person must have an ID document with them when moving around outside. A general 2+2 rule applies to moving around outside, according to which only 2 people can be in a public space together and a 2 metre distance must be kept from others.""
The stay-at-home order on Saaremaa and Muhu was lifted.
Travel restrictions between the islands and the mainland were lifted.
There have never been any stay-at-home orders, curfews or outside mask mandates in Finland. From 18 March, public gatherings of more than 10 persons were banned.
Travel to and from the Uusima region (including the capital Helsinki) was limited to those who have a ""valid reason"".
The government planned to impose a stay-at-home order in Helsinki and Turku end March 2021, but it was ruled out again due to legal concerns as it was found to be unconstitutional.
The movement restrictions were lifted.
The maximum size of gatherings was decided on the district level. Over some weeks, the smallest maximum size of public in a district was six.

From 17 March, a stay-at-home order was in place for the entire country and population. Exceptions were defined that included going to work, professional journeys which could not be postponed, making purchases in stores that remained open as they were deemed necessary, travel for health reasons, travel for imperative family reasons, for the assistance of vulnerable people and for childcare, and for short, individual physical activity or walking a pet, the latter two both only in the proximity of home. A document must be carried that indicates the reason of movement.

Another reason to leave the house has been introduced:  Travels on request of authorities (e.g. obligations to present to police or military, or missions of general interest). There have been several local rules including overnight curfews, sometimes only for minors (e.g. Hautmont, Jeumont, Colombes, Asnieres-sur-Seine, Puteaux, Courbevoie, etc.).

From 24 March, it was specified that leaving the house for physical activity,  exercise or pet walking was only allowed for one hour a day and within 1 km from home. It was only allowed to go alone or together with persons living in the same household.
The city of Sceaux introduced a universal mask mandate.
In Paris, physical activity was prohibited between 10 AM and 7 PM from 8 April (and still only allowed in a very restricted manner as above in the other times).
The mask mandate in Sceaux was taken back after a court ruled it to be possibly illegal.
The stay-at-home order expired and movement was now only restricted to remain within a 100 km radius.

While face masks have only been mandatory indoors before, on 29 July, prefectures were given the power to extend mask mandates to further public places. On 4 August, for instance, Paris made wearing masks obligatory in some streets and since 28 August, masks were mandatory everywhere in Paris.
A night curfew from 9 PM was set up in Paris and eight other big cities (Lille, Grenoble, Lyon, Aix-Marseille, Montpellier, Rouen, Toulouse, and Saint-Etienne).
On 24 October, the curfew was expanded to several other parts of France ffecting 46 million French residents.

A new stay-at-home order was decided on. As in the first lockdown, people needed a certificate to display the reason for being outside and physical activity was limited to one hour a day within 1 km around the place of residence.
From 28 November, the limit on physical activity was expanded to 3 hours within 20 km.
The stay-at-home order was replaced by a night curfew between 8 PM and 6 AM.
The curfew started at 6 PM from 2 January 2021 in some departements.
Masks have been made mandatory in more and more areas outdoors over the past weeks and were made mandatrory in all city centres from 3 January.
The curfew started at 6 PM from this day in all of Metropolitan France.
A weekend lockdown was imposed on some regions (in Cote d'Azur and Dunkirk) with physical activity being allowed within 5km of the place of residence.

From 19 March, in 16 departements, a new stay-at-home order was put in place, this time physical activity was allowed without a time limit outside of curfew times, but within 10 km from place of residence. This measure was subsequently expanded on further departements (3 on 25 March). The curfew hours were shifted to 7 PM to 6 AM.
On 3 April, the stay-at-home order with the 10 km limit that before was only valid in some departements was extended to entire metropolitan France.
The stay-at-home order was lifted again. The curfew remained in place, starting  at 7 PM and going until 6 AM.
From this day, the curfew started at 9 PM.
It’s not longer mandatory to wear masks outside.
The curfew was abolished.

Mitterteich, Bavaria, was the first German municipality to issue a stay-at-home order. Up to 2 April, residents had to stay home unless for important reasons such as going to work or caring for animals. Outside activities such as sport or going for a walk were not accepted as important reasons.
Several municipalities in the state of Baden-Wurttemberg have introduced bans on entering public places that still allowed for outdoor movement.

The first German state to issue a stay-at-home order was Bavaria. From 21 March, people needed a reason to leave their house. Going out for a walk or physical exercise was allowed alone or with people from the same household.

From 23 March, in 6 of 16 provinces, a stay-at-home order was in place (Bavaria, Berlin, Brandenburg, Saarland, Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt) Going out for a walk or for exercise was allowed everywhere, alone, with members of the same household, or (except for Bavaria) with one person from another household. While the rules on contacts were the same in the other 10 provinces, no stay-at-home orders were in place.
A strict local stay-at-home order and quarantine that didn't allow for outdoor leisure activities was passed in Neustadt, Thruringia (until 5/4).
A strict local stay-at-home order and quarantine that didn't allow for outdoor leisure activities was passed in Jessen, Saxony-Anhalt (until 6/4)

With the end of the quarantine in Jessen, only the stay-at-home orders of 6 of 16 provinces remain in place which all allow for outdoor sports and leisure activities when alone (or with one other person except for Bavaria)
The stay-at-home orders ended on 3 May.

The governors agreed that municipalities can order people to wear a mask in frequented areas when the 7 day incidence exceeds 35 / 100000. In the following days and weeks, most cities introduced mask mandates in some outside areas, sometimes in the entire city center (e.g. Halle (Saale), Gottingen, Leipzig, Aachen), sometimes just in few streets (e.g. Berlin, Hamburg, Cologne). In Dusseldorf, a mask mandate was placed on the entire city which was later taken back.
In the Bavarian municipality Rottal-Inn, a stay-at-home order was issued which was valid until 5 November. Sport and outdoor exercise (or going for a walk) remained allowed.
The stricter local lockdown measures in Rottal-Inn were lifted.
In Hildburghausen, Thuringia, a local stay-at-home order was issued which allowed for outdoor sports. Masks also have to be worn generally.
In Passau, Bavaria, a local stay-at-home order was issued which allowed for outdoor sports. Masks also have to be worn generally.
In December 2020, several German cities started to introduce curfews from 9 PM to 5 AM. From 4 December, a curfew was imposed in Mannheim, Baden-Wurttemberg.

A stay-at-home order was imposed in Bavaria from 9 December but physical exercise / walking outdoors were accepted as a reason to leave (outside stricter curfew times).  Also from 9 December, curfews were in place in Munich and Augsburg.

A curfew was put in place in the entire province of Baden-Wurttemberg. Other provinces followed in the subsequent weeks. During curfew times, people were only allowed to leave their house for important reasons, not including leisure or sports. The exact rules differed extremely between cities, so that it was difficult to make an assessment for the country as a whole.

A curfew was put in place in the entire province of Bavaria. Other provinces followed in the subsequent weeks. During curfew times, people were only allowed to leave their house for important reasons, not including leisure or sports. The exact rules differed extremely between cities, so that it was difficult to make an assessment for the country as a whole.

From 28 December to 23 January, in Eichsfeld, Thuringia, a stay-at-home order was imposed also on daytime movements.Individual exercise / movement at fresh air was allowed as a reason to leave the house.

On 5 January, it was decided that in all of Germany, people could not leave a radius of 15 km around their home municipality (or home address, depending on the state) if the incidence locally exceeded 200/100000. But not all states eventually implemented this rule.
The stay-at-home order during daytime in Bavaria was lifted.
In Schwabisch Hall (Baden-Wurttemberg) a stay-at-home order was imposed also during daytime. Leaving the house for exercise / walking was allowed.
The daytime stay-at-home order in Schwabisch-Hall was lifted.

As of 24 April, a federal law came into effect that automatically imposed a curfew from 10 PM to 5 AM if the incidence in a municipality is over 100 per 100000. Between 10 PM and midnight, going for a walk or exercising was still allowed alone (except from Bavaria). After midnight (and in Bavaria after 10 PM), only ""important reasons"" such as going to work or walking a dog count.
Since 9 May, curfews were not imposed on people who are completely vaccinated, have had Covid in the past 6 months, or have had Covid before and received their first vaccine shot.
In most places where masks were ever mandated, they are still mandated as of 15 May 2021 and overnight curfews continue to be rampant in many places.

The rules of the “federal emergency brake” automatically imposing curfews on municipalities with a 7-day incidence of over 100 per 100000 remained in place until 30 June. However, from 12 June on, no municipality exceeded this threshold.

The two villages Dragasia and Damaskinia in Voio, Kozani were put under quarantine. People were neither allowed to enter or exit the villages nor to freely circulate within these villages. The quarantine was lifted on 6 April.

All movement within Greece was banned with the exception of a set of reasons. Aside of working and essential shopping, this also included exercising individually or in pairs or walking a pet in the proximity of one's home. Citizens leaving their home were required to carry their ID or passport as well as some certification explaining the reason for their movement. This certification could be obtained either by filling a form on a special government website or by sending a free text message to a government number or it was possible to carry a handwritten declaration. These certifications needed to include the name, home adress, time of departure from home, and the reason for movement.

On 31 March and for a duration of 14 days, in some municipalities a nighttime curfew was imposed from 8 PM to 8 AM. The municipalities included Kastoria, Orestida, Nestoria, Xanthi, and Myki. At the same time, exceptions for outdoor exercise were abolished in these communities and walking pets was only allowed for 15 minutes a day.
On Mykonos and Santorini, a nighttime curfew was imposed from 8 PM to 8 AMl for 14 days.
The quarantine in Dragasia and Damaskinia was lifted.

On 9 April, a roma settlement in Larissa with approximately 3000 residents was put under a strict quarantine. While some media reports stated the entire settlement was put under quarantine, other sources claim that only few families were strictly quarantined thus it was probably not a local stay-at-home order but counts as a ""regular"" quarantine for contact persons and is not added to this data for now.
As no conflicting evidence was found, the harsher lockdown on Mykonos and Santorini presumably ended after 14 days as initially planned.
The quarantine in Larissa had ended.
Restriction of movement were lifted within the municipality and no certificate was needed anymore to leave the house.
After an outbreak in a roma settlement in Larissa, a local night curfew was imposed for 14 days and people were only allowed to leave their home with a mask.
Restrictions of movement outside the resident's prefecture were lifted.
As no conflicting evidence was found, the curfew and outside mask mandate in the roma settlement in Larissa presumably ended.
Residents of the village of Echinos, Xanthi were subject to a night curfew from 9 PM to 7 AM and were forced to wear a mask in all public places.
The night curfew in Echinos was converted into an all-day stay-at-home order.
The lockdown in Echinos ended.
As from 24 October, in regions with a high incidence, wearing masks has been made mandatory everywhere in public. Also, a curfew from 12:30 AM to 5 AM was established for these regions.

As of 3 November the curfew began at midnight. On this date, all geographical units were in the ""red"", ""yellow"", or ""grey"" categories thus outside mask mandates and curfews were in place. In grey areas, citizens were required to send a text message when they leave their house as in the first lockdown. In these areas, the curfew hours were 9 PM to 5 AM. People from grey geographical units were not allowed to leave their geographical unit either, but these units are larger than just one municipality.

From 7 November, similar measures as in the first lockdown were in place nationwide. Residents had to send a text message including their name, adress, and the reason why they leave their house to a specific government number. Physical exercise was allowed outdoors in the proximity to one's home and without a mask, but generally a mask had to be worn everywhere.

A stricter lockdown was imposed on Kalymnos island. Residents were only allowed to go to workplaces that remain open, to visit the doctor or pharmacy, to walk their pets or for shopping until 6 PM at the supermarket.

The six months lockdown ended. People no longer needed to send an SMS asking for permission to leave their house. Also, movement between regions was allowed again. A nighttime curfew remains between 00:30 and 05:00. On Kalymnos, the lockdown remained in force.
The lockdown on Kalymnos was lifted.
The start of the curfew is postponed to 1:30 AM.
Masks are no longer mandatory outdoors.
The night curfew was ended (it was already reintroduced in some places a few weeks later though)

From 27 March, people were only allowed to leave their house for work or basic needs. Reasons to leave the house included going to work, shopping for basic needs or work materials, caring for the elderly, administrative errands, health care utilization, fuelling the car, car repair, getting a haircut or manicure, taking children to child care, weddings, funerals, going to church, walking a pet, and open air recreational activities. The stay-at-home order initially was supposed to end on 11 April.
The curfew was prolonged.
The stay-at-home restrictions were lifted for the entire country with the exception of Budapest.
The stay-at-home restrictions were lifted for Budapest.
A curfew was imposed between midnight and 5 AM.

New curfew times were 8 PM to 5 AM. In some public spaces in larger towns, wearing masks was made compulsory. Mayors of towns with more than 10000 inhabitants could decide to make masks compulsory, e.g. in Budapest they were made compulsory in the largest part of the city. Masks could be taken off for individual exercise or in parks.
The curfew was suspended only for Christmas Eve.
Obligatory mask wearing in public places.
Curfew times were changed to 10 PM to 5 AM.
The curfew was changed to begin from 11 PM from this day.
The curfew and the outside mask mandate were abolished.

There have never been any stay-at-home orders, curfews or outside mask mandates in Iceland. People were free to leave their house or even their place of residence. Under the strictest restriction, the size of gatherings was limited to 10.
A ban of public gatherings of more than 20 persons came into effect (which lasted until 4 May). This was the strictest rule on gatherings in place during the first wave.
Public gatherings of more than 10 persons were restricted, which was the toughest restrictions on gatherings thus far.

A stay-at-home order was imposed. People aged 70 or older or with certain medical conditions were told to ""cocoon"" which included not leaving the house at all and even keeping distant from others within the household. For those younger than 70 and not suffering one of several medical conditions, brief individual exercise was allowed within a 2 km radius from home.

The ""cocooning"" policy was loosened so that older people could now leave their house if they avoid contact with other people. At the same time, the 2 km limit was converted to a 5 km limit in which exercise was allowed.
It was generally allowed to move within 20 km from home.

People were generally told to stay home again. Physical exercise remained allowed within 5 km from home. Travel outside the 5 km limit was only allowed for work, medical reasons, vital family reasons, attend a wedding or funeral, farming, or to visit a grave.
The movement restrictions were lifted again. People still had to stay in their county, unless for a set of allowed reasons.
From 24 December, tighter restrictions were in place again, but freedom of movement within the county was guaranteed, thus the measure does not count as a stay-at-home order.

People were generally told to stay home again. Physical exercise remained allowed within 5 km from home. Travel outside the 5 km limit was only allowed for work, education, or other ""essential purposes"".
Free movement (alone) within 20 km was allowed again.

On 23 February 2020, Italy put 11 villages under quarantine meaning that it was not allowed to enter or exit. Within the villages, all assemblies were banned, but was not prohibited to leave the house.

The quarantine was expanded on 14 provinces in Northern Italy from 8 March. From 8 March (Northern Italy) on, people needed to fill a form to leave their house stating their name, address and reason for leaving the house. It was allowed to leave for physical activity near from home.
On 9 March the regulations that previously were only valid for Northern Italy were expanded to the entire country with effect of the next day.
It was further clarified that physical activity was only allowed close from home.
As it was only allowed to go out alone, young children had no possibility to go out until 1 April when it was clarified that children could go out for a walk close from home together with a parent.
From 4 May, it was allowed to move within one's region, but a form still had to be carried.
From 18 May on, there was no need for authorization of movements anymore when moving within the municipality of residence. There were still strict regulations for moving between municipalities.
From 3 June, no certificate was needed for travel anymore.
Wearing face masks has been made obligatory in all public spaces on this day. They didn't have to be worn in ""isolated"" areas or when doing sport.

Mayors were given the power to impose local curfews after 9 PM on highly frequented streets or places. Starting from 22 October, the entire Lombardy Region had a curfew from 11 PM to 5 AM. In the next days, the regions Campania, Lazio, Sicilia, and Piemonte followed.

From this date, there was a nationwide curfew from 10 PM to 5 AM. In regions with relatively high infection rates (""scenario 4""), local stay-at-home orders were enforced with similar rules as in the first lockdown: To go out, you needed to be able to present a form stating the reason for being outside. Walks or other physical activity were allowed in the close vicinity of home. In the following months, several Italian provinces had been under stay-at-home orders. In the second most restrictive tier (""scenario 3""), movement was restricted to the municipality.

Temporarily there have been no regions under a stay-at-home order, even though this was constantly threatened if infection numbers rise. Several regions were under quarantine i.e. it was not allowed to leave the home municipality unless for an ""important reason"".
On New Year's Eve the curfew was from 10 PM until 7 AM.
Some provinces were put under ""scenario 4"" again, implying a stay-at-home order.
All provinces were outside of ""scenario 4"" from this day.
From this day, some provinces were under ""scenario 4"" again, implying a stay-at-home order.
All provinces were moved outside of ""scenario 4"". Some remained in scenario 3.
The beginning of curfew was postponed from 10 PM to 11 PM from this day.
All regions are under scenario 2 now, thus travel between municipalities was allowed again across the whole country and a curfew between 11 PM and 5 AM applied.
The first two regions moved to scenario 1 where no curfew applied.

From this day, all regions are under scenario 1. Note that the scenarios are automatically imposed dependent on the incidence and curfews were reintroduced some weeks later as case numbers rose again.

The government prohibited the circulation of citizens and private vehicles between 10 AM and 4 PM and from 8 PM to 6 AM ""except for medical needs, production, supply and sale of essential goods and for services and activities related to pandemic management"".
On 28 March, curfew hours were changed to 5 PM to 6 AM.
Two towns in Northern Kosovo were put under quarantine including a stay-at-home order. People could only go out to buy food and medicine.

Movement of persons was restricted to 90 minutes per day during a time slot based on the the penultimate digit of the ID. In these 90 minutes, it was allowed to move alone in order to perform financial tasks, seek medical help, or purchase essential items. Mouth and nose had to be covered at all times when outside the house.
Citizens were now allowed to move (but covering mouth and nose) for 4 hours a day within two timeslots of 120 minutes each, according to their ID number.
A nighttime curfew from 9 PM to 5 AM was introduced.
Freedom of movement was restored. I could find no reports on whether the outdoors mask mandate being lifted, but reports about a mask mandate either still being in place or being introduced in July.
A curfew from 9 PM to 5 AM was introduced in several municipalities.

Wearing masks in public places has been made required by law. All citizens aged more than 65, and others who suffer from chronic diseases, were only be allowed outside their homes from 5 AM and 10 AM and between 6 PM and 9 PM.

Curfew times were shifted to 10.30 PM to 5 AM, but now citizens aged over 65 as well as those suffering from one of several defined chronic illnesses were only allowed to move freely between 5 AM and 10 AM as well as between 6 PM and 9 PM. The curfew was applied in in the municipalities of Prishtina, Prizren, Peja, Podujevo, Gjakova, Ferizaj, Lipjan, Drenas, Vushtrri, South Mitrovica, Gjilan, Fushe Kosove and Strpce. Movement restrictions for risk groups are not specified to be valid only in some regions, so I assume they were in force everywhere.
The curfew applies at Pristina, Prizren, Pec, Podujevo, Gjakova, Ferizaj, Lipljan, Glogovac, Vucitrn, Mitrovica South, Gjilan, Kosovo Polje and Strpce.
The nightly curfew was lifted.
Persons over 65 were only allowed to go outside from 6 AM to 10 AM and from 4 PM to 7 PM.

From 13 November on, municipalities were classified into different zones according to the infection numbers. In the municipalities in the ""red zone"", a curfew from 7 PM was put in place. Entry and exit from red zones was also restricted at least during the weekend or at night.

change: The curfew and movement restrictions for the elderly were abolished.
A curfew from 10 PM to 5 AM was imposed. On 19 April,  which was still the case on 15 May.
Curfew hours were changed to 10.30 PM to 5 AM
Masks will no longer be mandatory outdoors as of 1 July.
Gatherings were banned on this day, but no stay-at-home restrictions were introduced
Only two persons were allowed to meet, keeping 2m distance from each other.
The so called 2 plus 2 rule was reintroduced, i.e. only 2 persons were allowed to meet, keeping 2m distance.
Over New Year's (from 30 December to 4 January) and subsequently on Fridays and Saturdays, a curfew was imposed from 10 PM to 5 AM the following morning.
The weekend curfew was discontinued.

There have been no stay-at-home orders, curfews, or outside mask mandates in Liechtenstein. From 22 March on, gatherings of more than 5 persons were banned. The government threatened a stay-at-home order but eventually did not impose one.
Only two persons were allowed to meet in public areas (exluding members of the same family)

Face masks were made mandatory in all public areas. From 10 April 8 PM to 13 April 8 PM, all inter-municipality travel was banned. Apart from this, even though the country was under a self-labelled ""quarantine"" people could freely move alone, with members of the same household, or with one person of another household.

The town of Nemencine was quarantined. Only those who live or work there were allowed in, others needed a special permission. Leaving the town was allowed for work and health reasons. Within Nemencine, movement was not restricted.
As no opposing sources were found, I assume that the quarantine ended as planned.
Wearing face masks was no longer mandatory in outdoor spaces (but recommended).
The municipalities were classified into one of three risk zones. In ""red zones"", among other strict rules (e.g. gatherings of only up to 5 people), masks were made mandatory inside and outside.

A second ""quarantine"" was imposed on the entire country. Rules were similar to the ones formerly valid in red zones, including mandatory face masks in all public places. Exceptions included during physical exercise and outside of towns when a distance of 20 (sic) metres to others is ensured. Gatherings of more than five persons, excluding family members, in public places were prohibited
The number of people allowed to gather was reduced from 5 to 2.

People needed to stay home and were only allowed to leave to go shopping (in the same municipality only), to work, to attend a funeral, or to seek healthcare. Walks within the municipality, alone or with members of the same household were allowed as well. On 20 January 2021, the government also allowed single households to interact with one other household.
Masks were no longer required outdoors if a distance of 2 metres is kept to others.  Also, the movement between a city's metropolitan area and the surrounding district was allowed.
As of 6 March, two households or up to five people were allowed in public.
Travel between most municipalities was allowed in many places, but restrictions remained in 16 municipalities.
Travel restrictions between municipalities were expanded on the entire country again over Easter.
Travel restrictions between municipalities ended.
The stay-at-home order was eliminated from the national quarantine directive. Strict rules on gatherings remain.
The use of public spaces was restricted to a set of reasons. These included individual recreational activities alone or with members of the same household.
The restrictions on going out were lifted and replaced with rules that only addresses gatherings.
A curfew between 11 PM and 6 AM was imposed.
From 26 December, the curfew began at 9 PM. The curfew was still in place on 15 May. As of 16 May, the curfew started at midnight.
From this day, the curfew began at 11 PM again.
The night curfew began at midnight from this day.
The curfew was lifted.

Anyone over 65 years, pregnant women, as well as people with a set of medical problems must stay home. They were allowed outside only for attending medical appointments, to buy food, medicine, and other necessities, and for ""absolutely essential or urgent"" needs. People who live with others who are locked down also must stay home, but there were further exceptions which included going to work, and excercising child custody or visitation rights.
The ""vulnerable groups"" were allowed to go outside again.
Masks had to be worn in all public places from this day, inside and outside.
From July, fully vaccinated people are allowed to go out without wearing a mask when alone or with one other vaccinated person.
The villages Balceana and Sofia were put under quarantine.

On 21 March, the town of Sangerei was put under quarantine. The movement through the town was restricted ""in particular after 10 PM"". Only people who need to make purchases or need the services of the Public Services Agency were allowed to circulate.

Access to public places such as parks and playgrounds were limited. Persons older than 63 were forced to stay home unless they go to work, see a doctor, make purchases, or have ""other justified reasons"" like caring for a pet.
Identification papers must be carried to prove a valid reason to be out. Up to three people were allowed together in public spaces.

In the de facto independently governed region of Transnistria, a stay-at-home order was imposed as of 1 April. Leaving the house was only allowed in exceptional cases buying food or pharmacies at the nearest shop, to assist people in need of care, or to work. It was later clarified that walking with a child to fresh air was welcome, but ""aimless walking on the streets"" would not be tolerated.

While the stay-at-home order for people over 63 remains, others (outside of quarantined zones) were not subject to it anymore, yet movement of more than two persons remains banned. People over 63 may go outside for work reasons or between 9 AM and 1 PM for other essential reasons (purchasing food or medicine)
