change: The curfew in Balti and Chisinau was discontinued.

It is unclear when the outside mask mandate for the entire country fell. From later articles, it is clear that at some point, the outside mask mandate was not in place everywhere anymore. That is clear because wearing masks outside was not longer mandated in Chisinau from 27 May. On 2 May, the Moldovan president said people should wear masks in closed spaces, thus I assume that it was already allowed to go out without a mask in parts of Moldova at that day.

I found no recent update on the rules, but according to both the Austrian and the British governments' websites, the stay-at-home order for people over 63 as well as the outside mask mandate were still in place on 15 May 2021.
Wearing masks was no longer mandatory outside in Chisinau. It’s unclear whether there are still outside mask mandate in other cities.
I found no update on the stay-at-home for elderly people
Circulation was restricted to essential employment, grocery shopping, family assistance or childcare, health reasons, leaving pets, and exercise.
Playgrounds, public gardens, and access to the coast were closed. Going for a walk alone or with members of the same household was allowed.
The stay-at-home order was lifted.
Wearing a mask was made mandatory in some parts of Monaco.
A curfew from 8 PM to 6 AM was imposed. Wearing masks has been made mandatory on the entire territory.
From 11 January, it was from 7 PM to 6 AM.
The start of the curfew was postponed to 8 PM.
Since 18 April until 3 May, the curfew was from 9 PM to 6 AM.
Wearing a mask was no longer mandated outdoors except for some places and some streets.
The curfew was abolished.
For the town of Tuzi, an unconditional stay-at-home order was imposed. In the rest of the country, people could still freely circulate alone or with one other person.
A nationwide curfew was imposed from 7 PM to 5 AM Monday to Friday and from 1 PM on Saturday to 5 AM on Monday. All ""sports and recreational activities"" were banned on all public areas.
From 5 April, the curfew hours were changed to 7 PM to 5 AM on weekdays and 1 PM to 5 AM on weekends.

It seems that there wasn't  any ban on recreational activities anymore when alone following 8 April, but just a ban on the presence of persons on beaches, bathing areas and picnic areas. Yet, given that the responsible government body announced that individual outdoor activity was allowed from 21 April, the stay-at-home order presumably remained in place. There was a curfew from Sunday 11 AM to Monday 5 AM.
The quarantine of Tuzi has ended. One member of a family was allowed to go out.

From 15 April 2020, there was a curfew from 7 PM to 5 AM on weekends, Saturday between 1 PM and 5 AM, and Sunday 11 AM to 5 PM. Persons with pets were allowed to be out for 60 minutes within curfew times.
From 21 April, citizens were allowed to leave their house every day until 11 PM. The national coordination body also stated that outdoor activities would be allowed individually.
The curfew was lifted as well as many other restrictions (such as just being allowed to outside alone / with members of the same household).
A 6 PM to 5 AM curfew was imposed on Rozaje. Also, Masks were made mandatory in all public areas in Bijelo Polje.
Masks were made mandatory in public spaces in the entire Northern region.
Masks were made mandatory in public spaces in Podgorica.
Masks now had to be worn in all public places throughout the country. The curfew in Rozaje was shortened to 10 PM to 5 AM.
It was clarified that masks don't have to be worn on beaches and in national parks.

From 28 September, a 10 PM to 5 AM curfew was automatically imposed on municipalities that exceed a distinguished number of infections. Other restrictions in this category included a ban on receiving visitors outside the family. In the beginning, these were Niksic, Berane, and Andrijevica.
From 15 November, a curfew from 9 PM to 5 AM was imposed on the entire country. Traffic between municipalities was banned over the weekends.
From 25 November, curfew times were extended to 7 PM to 5 AM. Curfew times seem to have been shortened to 10 PM to 5 AM later, but different sources are a bit contradictory.
As of 29 April, curfew times were from midnight to 5 AM and masks were still mandatory everywhere. There was no curfew on 1 May.
The curfew was lifted as well as the ban on travelling between municipalities on weekends.

During the first wave of the pandemic, no curfews, stay-at-home orders or outside mask mandates were imposed on the Dutch. It was prohibited to be in public with groups of more than 3 persons if no distance was kept.
The curfew was not prolonged.
Amsterdam and Rotterdam introduced a mask mandate on several busy streets and places.
The outside mask mandate in areas of Amsterdam and Rotterdam ended.

While before it was possible to be outside alone or with one other person, from this day on, a curfew was imposed from 9 PM to 4.30 AM. Exceptions were work-related circulation, supporting medical assistance to a human or animal, provide informal care, walking a dog alone, urgent family matters, funerals, exams related to vocational or higher education, and live TV. When outside during curfew hours, a personal declaration had to be carried unless in cases of emergency, when just arrived from abroad (proven by travel tickets), or when walking a dog.
The curfew was lifted.

On 13 March, the municipalities of Debar and Centar Zupa were quarantined. This included a ban on all movement in or out, but I found no reports about whether citizens were not allowed to move within these towns.
From 22 March, restrictions on movement between 9 PM and 6 AM were enforced.
On 24 March, curfew hours were revised to end at 5 AM.
From 25 March, the rules were further strictened so that people over 67 were only allowed to go outside from 5 AM to 11 AM and minors of age were only allowed outside between noon and 9 PM.

From 26 March, curfew hours were 4 PM to 5 AM on Saturdays and Sundays. In this time, movement was only allowed for pet owners and their pets between 8 PM and 8.30 PM within 100m or 200m (different information found) from the place of residence.

A complete ban on movement during the weekend was imposed on the municipality of Kumanovo. On weekends, only police, army, health professionals, and farmers were allowed to move around and exclusively for work.

walk_day: no, but locally for some groups
no, but locally for some groups

change: From 8 April, curfew times were shifted to 4 PM to 5 AM on weekdays and to 4 PM on Friday until 5 AM on Monday over the entire weekend with the same exceptions as in Kumanovo before. There were three time frames of 30 minutes each on weekend days where people were allowed to walk a pet within 100 m from the house. Much stricter time frames were decided on for people over 67 or under 18. Citizens were not allowed to gather in public with more than one other person.
The local stricter lockdown in Debar and Centar Zupa was lifted. There is conflicting information on whether this happened on 12 April already.
Movement in all ""picnic places, parks and forests"" was already banned from 16 April 4 PM to 21 April, 5 AM.
From Friday 17 April 4 PM to Tuesday, 21 April 5 AM, no movement was allowed.
As of 22 April, masks had to be worn at all public places in Kumanovo, Tetovo, and Prilep.

As of 23 April, weekday curfews were from 7 PM to 5 AM and on the weekend all circulation was banned between Saturday 3 PM until Monday 5 AM. Elderly were only allowed to go out between 5 AM and noon on weekdays and between 5 AM and 11 AM on Saturdays, minors between 1 PM and 7 PM on weekdays and between noon and 3 PM on Saturdays. People had to wear face masks, but not outside when a distance of 2m was kept to others.
There was a temporary tightening of curfew hours over the 1 May weekend.
The weekend curfew was relaxed. It was allowed to leave the house between 5 AM and 7 PM on all days of the week.

Following a decision of the Constitutional Court, from 16 May, the rules for elderly and minors were lifted and the same curfew hours applied for the entire population thereafter. This meant that all people were banned from circulating between 7 PM and 5 AM.

It is unclear at what time the mandate ended that was in place for all public spaces, even when keeping a distance, but recent news from one of the affected municipalities stated it was only mandatory when not keeping distance.
There was another complete lockdown between 24 May 11 AM and 26 May 5 AM.
The holiday lockdown ended and curfew times were applied again as before.
The curfew was lifted.

A complete ban on the movement of citizens of Skopje, ""including every municipality, in Kumanovo, Tetovo, Shtip as well as the surrounding municipality in Skopje: Arachinovo, Zelenikovo, Ilinden, Petrovec, Lipkovo, Studenicani, Karbinci, Bogovinje, Brvenica, Tearce, Zelino and Jegunovce"" from 9 PM on 4 June until 5 AM on 8 June. In all other municipalities, curfew hours were 9 PM to 5 AM on 4 June and 4 PM to 5 AM from 5 June to 7 June.

A complete ban on the movement of citizens of Skopje, ""including every municipality, in Kumanovo, Tetovo, Shtip as well as the surrounding municipality in Skopje: Arachinovo, Zelenikovo, Ilinden, Petrovec, Lipkovo, Studenicani, Karbinci, Bogovinje, Brvenica, Tearce, Zelino and Jegunovce"" from 9 PM on 4 June until 5 AM on 8 June. In all other municipalities, curfew hours were 9 PM to 5 AM on 4 June and 4 PM to 5 AM from 5 June to 7 June.

A complete ban on the movement of citizens of Skopje, ""including every municipality, in Kumanovo, Tetovo, Shtip as well as the surrounding municipality in Skopje: Arachinovo, Zelenikovo, Ilinden, Petrovec, Lipkovo, Studenicani, Karbinci, Bogovinje, Brvenica, Tearce, Zelino and Jegunovce"" from 9 PM on 4 June until 5 AM on 8 June. In all other municipalities, curfew hours were 9 PM to 5 AM on 4 June and 4 PM to 5 AM from 5 June to 7 June.

A complete ban on the movement of citizens of Skopje, ""including every municipality, in Kumanovo, Tetovo, Shtip as well as the surrounding municipality in Skopje: Arachinovo, Zelenikovo, Ilinden, Petrovec, Lipkovo, Studenicani, Karbinci, Bogovinje, Brvenica, Tearce, Zelino and Jegunovce"" from 9 PM on 4 June until 5 AM on 8 June. In all other municipalities, curfew hours were 9 PM to 5 AM on 4 June and 4 PM to 5 AM from 5 June to 7 June.
People now had to wear a mask everywhere in public, even outside and alone.
An overnight curfew from 10 PM to 5 AM was imposed. Was suspended during Easter and Eid-al-fitr. From 5 May, curfew times were 11 PM to 5 AM and since 12 May midnight to 4 AM.
The start of curfew was postponed to 8 PM.
The start of curfew was postponed to 8 PM.
There was no curfew over Orthodox Easter from 1 May to 2 May.
The start of curfew was postponed to 11 PM.
There was no curfew that night due to Eid-al Fitr / Ramadan Bayram holiday
The start of curfew was postponed to 11 PM.
The obligation to wear masks no longer applies outside.
The curfew was lifted.
A stay-at-home order was issued. People were allowed to go out to go to supermarkets, pharmacies, gas stations, hospitals, and banks, but not to exercise.
A curfew was imposed between 9 PM and 6 AM. It is unclear what differences that made given that movements were already banned during the day.
A ban on movements between districts was imposed.
The ban on travels between districts was prolonged until 30 April.
Face masks were made mandatory in all public areas.
The ban on travels being districts was likely prolonged until 15 May.
As of 8 May (at the latest), the daytime stay-at-home order was only in place on Sundays and the night curfew for all nights.
The Sunday curfew was lifted. Only the night curfew remains, but was shortened to the time between midnight and 6 AM.
Curfew times were changed to midnight to 6 AM.
The night curfew was lifted.
From 31 December until 4 January, a curfew was imposed between 10 PM and 5 AM.
From 31 December until 4 January, a curfew was imposed between 10 PM and 5 AM.
Another night curfew from 10 PM to 5 AM was imposed.

The regions Girna and Nikosia were locked down. Leaving the house was only allowed for a set of reasons not including exercise and most businesses remain closed. Leaving these two regions was not allowed.

The stay-at-home order was extended to the whole territory of Northern Cyprus. The stay-at-home order was prelonged until 22 February, 5 AM. I found no source about it being lifted, but also no source about it being prolonged. Apparently, it was lifted on this day, but a night curfew and a Sunday curfew remained. In the beginning of May, there was still a curfew between 9 PM and 5 AM every night and between Saturday 9 PM and Sunday 5 AM.
The stay-at-home order and ban on leaving the district were prolonged until 10 February.
The stay-at-home order was prolonged until 22 February, 5 AM.

From 22 February, some restrictions were eased. I found no source explicitly saying so, but presumably that includes lifting the daytime stay-at-home order. Sources from April and May say, a curfew was in place every night and on Sundays.
The ban on travels between districts ended.
A curfew every night from 9 PM to 5 AM as well as from Saturday 9 PM to Sunday 5 AM was prolonged.
The curfew was changed to 10.30 PM to 5 AM on all days of the week. At least that was decided 3 weeks before, it is not clear whether this decision was really implemented

I found no update on the curfew or outside mask mandate being lifted. At least the curfew was apparently lifted at some point, presumably in June. This has to be the case because I found news saying it was introduced on 12 July.

Norway has never introduced stay-at-home orders or curfews. Wearing a mask was never mandatory outside and is not even mandatory inside on a national level, but in cities such as Oslo it is. It was allowed to gather outside with up to 5 people at all times.

As of 25 March, it was only allowed to be outside for ""necessary everyday activities"". These included going to work, shopping, medical visits, walking dogs, jogging, cycling, and walking provided that no more than 2 people are outside together (except for family).

From 1 April on, people were banned from going out except for going to work (where working from home is not possible), volunteering to fight the pandemic, or dealing with matters necessary for every day life (e.g. medical visits, shopping for groceries and medicine, caring for relatives) walking pets. Apparently, sports and leisure activities were not allowed in public anymore. Parks, boulevards, and beaches were closed. Minors may only go out together with an adult.
Mouth and nose had to be covered at all public places.

From 20 April on, it was allowed to go outside for recreational purposes. Forests and parks were opened again. Recreational activity was allowed. Also minors over 13 were allowed to go out alone again.
Mouth and nose had no longer to be covered in open spaces if a distance of 2 m is kept to others.
Depending on the incidence, the country was divided into different zones. In ""red zones"", mouth and nose have to be covered at all pubilc places.
The obligation to cover mouth and nose was extended to the entire country.

From 24 October, people under 16 years of age were only allowed outside under the care of an adult between 8 AM and 4 PM. People over 70 should not go out at all, but this does not seem to be mandatory.
A New Year's curfew was imposed from 31 December 7 PM until 1 January 6 AM. People were not allowed to go from one place to another during that time.
A New Year's curfew was imposed from 31 December 7 PM until 1 January 6 AM.
Masks had not to be worn outside anymore.

People were mandated to stay home. People aged 70 or older and those with certain health conditions were only allowed to go out to make essential purchases, health care provision or pet walking. For people under 70, it was additionally allowed to leave home in order go to work if working from home is not possible, visiting vulnerable people who need help, family reasons, judicial reasons, going to the bank or post office, volunteering, short walks, short physical exercise.
Over Easter, travelling outside the own county of residence was banned.

The state of emergency ended and with it ended the total lockdown for elderly people. Short walks remain allowed, individually or with members of the same household. Further reasons to leave the house were introduced, e.g. fishing.
The stay-at-home order was lifted.
A stay-at-home order was imposed on the municipalities of Felgueiras, Lousada and Pacos de Ferreira. Among other exceptions, it was allowed to leave the house for a short individual walk or exercise.
From 28 October, a mask had to be worn in all of Portugal if a distance of 2 m to others cannot be kept.
Between 30 October and 3 November, citizens were only allowed to circulate within their municipality.
The stay-at-home order was extended to 121 municipalities. Between 30 October and 3 November, citizens were only allowed to circulate within their municipality.
In the high incidence municipalities where a stay-at-home order was in place, a curfew between 11 PM and 5 AM was imposed on weekdays and between 1 PM and 5 AM on weekends.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again for the time between 27 November 11 PM and 2 December 5 AM as well as between 4 December 11 PM and 9 December 5 AM.
From 1 December, there were municipalities with a curfew as before and others with a lower incidence where the curfew was 11 PM to 5 AM on all days.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again for the time between 27 November 11 PM and 2 December 5 AM as well as between 4 December 11 PM and 9 December 5 AM.
On Christmas night, the curfew did not start before 2 AM.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again between 12 AM on 31 December and 5 AM on 4 January.
. On the first three days of January 2021, the curfew started on 1 PM.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again between 12 AM on 31 December and 5 AM on 4 January.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again between 11 PM on 8 January and 5 AM on 11 January.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again between 11 PM on 8 January and 5 AM on 11 January.

A stay-at-home order for the entire nation was put in place again. Rules were similar to the first lockdown but without the stricter orders for elderly. For all age groups, it was allowed to go out to make essential purchases,for accessing public services, for health care provision, pet walking, in order go to work if working from home was not possible, visiting vulnerable people who need help, family reasons, judicial reasons, going to the bank or post office, volunteering, short walks, open-air physical exercise, and some other ""essential reasons"".
Circulation between municipalities was banned again.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again over the Easter holidays.
Circulation between municipalities was banned again over the Easter holidays. Enjoying time at fresh air was still restricted to a short time close from home.
The dwellings Longueira-Almograve and Sao Teotonio in Odemira municipality were quarantined. Entry and exit was only allowed for a limited set of reasons.

The state of emergency was replaced by a state of calamity. According to the government website, in most municipalities all individual outdoor activities were allowed again, but there remained to be restrictions in some municipalities: Odemira, Portimao, Aljezur, Resende, Carregal do Sal, Paredes, Miranda do Douro and Valongo. However, in the actual law it still said ""Citizens should refrain from circulating on public spaces and roads, as well as on private spaces and roads deemed to be public roads, and should remain at home, avoiding unnecessary travel."" thus I interpret this as a stay-at-home order with broad exceptions (none were specified anymore) or little enforcement. But it didn't limit movement on a short duration around home anymore and even cafes were open again.
Portimao and Aljezur were released from stricter lockdown.

All Odemira parishes are released from stricter local lockdown rules. Unfortunately, I couldn’t find information on whether and when restrictions in the other municipalities were lifted that remained in phase 3 of deconfinement. As I found no news on these municipalities, I assume, the stricter stay-at-home orders everywhere were lifted from that day.
The update of the regulations under the state of calamity doesn’t include a civic duty to stay home anymore.
Travel from and to Lissabon was restricted over the weekends.
As of 1 July, curfews were reintroduced in municipalities with high incidences.
A curfew from 10 PM to 6 AM was imposed. During the day, movement was allowed with a maximum of 3 people.

A stay-at-home order was imposed. Persons over the age of 65 had to remain home at all times. Others were allowed to leave for work with a signed note from their employer, and to buy groceries. The army joined the police in controlling the stay-at-home order.
Some villages were additionally put under quarantine in the next days: Suceave from 30 March until 13 May and Tandarei from 4 April until 11 May.
The quarantine of Suceave ended.
It was allowed to move freely within the municipality, but a permission was needed to travel elsewhere.
People could travel freely to other municipalities again.

Following a new quarantine law, Cartojani in Giurgiu county was the first village to be quarantined under the new law. Many more municipalities followed over the next months, too many to handle in this dataset for now, so the ban on leaving municipality was in force at most times for some villages.
Masks were made required in some open spaces
Wearing a face mask has been made mandatory everywhere in the capital, Bucharest.

Petrova, Maramures County, was put under quarantine. According to the automated translation of the legislation, this includes a ban on all movement except the most necessary. Sic and Savadisla in Cluj county were also put under quarantine on this day.
Several local quarantines followed over the next weeks, at least some included local stay-at-home orders.
A curfew between 11 PM and 5 AM was imposed and masks have been made mandatory in all public spaces.
No exact information on local lockdowns was found. There might have been days when no municipality was under  a stay-at-home order.

A local lockdown including a stay-at-home order and quarantine of municipality was imposed on Dumbravita, Sag, Sandra si Nitchidorf in Timis county. There have been numerous other local lockdowns, but I found no sources in languages in English or German.
The start of the night curfew was changed to 10 PM.
From this day, he night curfew began at 8 PM on Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays everwhere and every day in municipalities with a high incidence.
The nighttime curfew was lifted for the Orthodox Easter night (1 May to 2 May)

Presumably the last municipalities came out of quarantine. This might have happened earlier, the last lifted local lockdown I found was on 28 April but as I don't speak Romanian and relied on automated trranslation, I might have missed some.
The nighttime curfew was lifted for the Qadr night during the month of Ramadan (8 May to 9 May)
The curfew and the outside mask mandate were lifted.

Moscow citizens over the age of 65, as well as some citizens with diagnosed chronic conditions, were compelled to go to quarantine, initially until 1 May, but this was later prolonged. There were exempts for healthcare workers or managers or some other essential staff.
walk_day: yes, but not locally for some groups
walk_night: yes, but not locally for some groups

walk_day: yes, but not locally for some groups
walk_night: yes, but not locally for some groups

walk_day: yes, but not locally for some groups
walk_night: yes, but not locally for some groups

change: A stay-at-home order was imposed in Chechnya.

In Moscow, from 30 March, people were only allowed to go out to the nearest grocery shop or pharmacy, for approved essential work, for emergencies, or to walk their dog within a 100 m distance from home.
Similar orders as those in Chechnya and Moscow were announced in nearly all other parts of the country. On 1 April, 75 out of 85 subdivisions had issued stay-at-home orders.
From 15 April, a permit was needed for the use of any means of transport in Moscow, private or public.

Changes in Moscow: From 1 June on, outdoor sports and walks were allowed three times a week according to a schedule. A mask had to be worn in all public places. Unfortunately, there are few English sources on lockdowns in other provinces.

The stay-at-home order in Moscow was lifted. According to Deutsche Welle, Moscow was the last place in Russia with a stay-at-home order. There is some conflicting evidence as to whether Moscow was the last city that restored freedom of movement.
From 13 July on, masks were not longer mandatory outside in Moscow.
In two cities and five districts of the Republic of Bashkortostan, only residents may circulate and they may only do so with special passes.

In Moscow, all people over 65 years of age must remain home. They may shop rarely, but walks outside remain unrestricted. It is not completely clear whether there was indeed a stay-at-home order as many news reports say that the elderly were only advised to stay home. Regarding the movement restrictions in Bashkortostan, I could not find an end date.
The stay-at-home order for elderly people in Moscow was lifted.
Movement was only allowed for work, health reasons or emergencies. It was forbidden to walk for leisure reasons.
The stay-at-home order was lifted. Movement was allowed while respecting social distancing rules (no gatherings, keeping a distance, wearing masks when close to others)
A curfew from 00.30 to 6 AM was imposed.
The curfew was changed to 10 PM at least for some days.
At least from 7 January, the curfew times were 10 PM to 5 AM.
It was mandated to wear masks outdoors.
Over Easter (3 to 5 April), the curfew started at 8 PM.
The curfew ended.
For vaccinated people, masks were no longer mandatory outside.
Masks are no longer mandatory outdoors.

A strict curfew was imposed on all citizens from 8 PM to 5 AM. For those older than 65 in places with more than 5000 inhabitants, and older than 70 years everywhere, a strict stay-at-home order was imposed, i.e. movement was restricted not only during curfew hours. Elderly people may only leave to go to selected grocery stores on Sundays between 3 AM and 8 AM (later rom 4 AM to 7 AM).
The curfew was extended to 5 PM to 5 AM, a ban on public transport was set in place, spending time in parks and public spaces intended for recreation and sport was banned.
The curfew was extended to last from 3 PM Saturday to 3 AM Sunday and from 3 PM Sunday to 5 AM Monday.
The weekend curfew was expanded, to Saturday 1 PM - Monday 5 AM from 2 April.
The curfew was extended to Friday 5 PM to Monday 5 AM from 9 April.
Over Easter, a complete curfew was in place from Friday 17 April 5 PM to Tuesday 21 April 5 AM.

The Government announced that as of April 20, citizens over the age of 65 would be allowed to go out three times a week for half an hour and 300 meters away from their home. It was also announced that children with autism and other disabilities and their parents will be allowed to have a walk during the curfew up to 200 meters away from home. ""
As of 27 April, persons over 65 were allowed to go for a walk for one hour between 6 PM and 1 AM.
The state of emergency and the related stay-at-home policies were lifted.
On 7 July, a new curfew was announced by the presidents but following protests and riots, these plans were cancelled before they were implemented.

Some sources claim that Serbia introduced a universal mask mandate including outdoor areas on that day. Yet, according to the European Observatory on Health Systems and Policies, masks were only recommended outdoors, but mandated indoors.
Face masks were made mandatory in all public areas.

It was only allowed to go out for travelling to and from work, shopping essentials, delivering products to help neighbours, urgent health reasons, taking a trip to nature (but just within a district or within the cities of Bratislava and Kosice), going to a funeral, or for looking after a relative who needs care (also just within a district/city)

Five roma settlements in Eastern Slovakia were put under quarantine. Apparently there was no strict quarantine within the settlements, but as these are just settlements within a village, I assume that there is little space and it's more of a stay-at-home order that does, in practice, not allow for outdoor activity. Also, a mayor is cited in the sourced article telling residents to stay home.
The end of the Easter lockdown.
The quarantine in Bystrany was lifted.
The quarantine in three settlements in Krompachy was lifted.
On 15 May, the last quarantined Roma settlement (in Zehra) was freed.
Masks were not longer required when outside.
Masks were required outside again.
A stay-at-home order was set in place again. There were several exceptions including meeting one other household (and always the same) as well as individual sport and outdoor activities.
The rules were tightened so that it was only allowed to stay in nature within the district of residence A mass screening was performed.

A mass screening was performed. With a negative test, as of 27 January, exceptions from the stay-at-home order remained similar to those before. In districts with a small incidence, measures were loosened. For districts with higher rates of positive tests in the mass screening, those between 15 and 65 who did not do a test were not granted the same exceptions from the curfew. Outdoor activities were not allowed for them anymore except from walking cats or dogs within 1000m from residence.

From 8 February, a ""traffic light"" system was introduced. In high incidence areas, a negative test was required on a weekly basis in order to go outside as before, in other areas the frequency of testing was lower.
Most exceptions from the stay-at-home order were only granted between 5 AM and 8 PM. After 8 PM, a stricter curfew was in place with the only exceptions of work and emergencies.

A test to travel to another district was only longer required in tier 4 districts. Outdoors, masks were only mandatory when a distance of 5m (or 2m according to a table in linked news article) was kept. This is likely impossible in cities.

In districts with a higher incidence, there remained a stay-at-home order from 5 AM to 1 AM with a stricter night curfew from 9 PM to 1 AM whereas in most regions, only the night curfew from 9 PM to 1 AM remained in place. Travelling outside the district was allowed outside curfew times.

The national state of emergency was lifted including the national curfew. In districts in the red or dark red tier, a curfew from 9 PM to 1 AM remained in place. In the dark red tier, a curfew from 5 AM to 9 PM applies, too. Restrictions remained locally. Wearing masks was still required outside when closer than 5m to people of other households, which is probably hard to avoid in cities. In the red, dark red, and orange tiers, wearing a mask was mandated outdoors whenever closer than 2m to someone outside the own household.
Only three districts remained in the red tier and thus had a curfew and daytime restrictions on movement. (Bianska Stiavnica, Kysucke Nove Mesto, and Myjava)
Three districts remained with curfew and restrictions on movement.
Bianska Stiavnica moved to the “light red” tier, only 2 districts remained under curfew.
Myjava was the last district to remain under curfew and movement restrictions.
No district was under a curfew anymore. The same rules were still in place, with curfews and stay-at-home orders automatically imposed if the local incidence was high enough.

Gatherings and movement of people in public were banned. It was allowed to leave home to work, for medical reasons or to buy groceries at the closest shop. People were also allowed to go outdoors and to parks, but only with people living in the same household.
People now needed a reason to leave their municipality. Going to parks was only allowed within the municipality of residence.

People were free to travel outside their municipality as they are within. It is unclear to what extent outdoor activities were allowed. It seems that individual movement such as swimming was allowed while sunbathing is not.
The epidemic officially ended and gatherings of up to 200 people were allowed again. I don't find it stated explictly that freedom of movement was restored, but it seems to be like that.
Wearing face masks in open spaces was made mandatory where it is not possible to maintain a distance of 2m.
A curfew from 9 PM to 6 AM was imposed. Movement between regions was banned with some exceptions. Wearing face masks in open spaces was made mandatory inependent of the distaance to others.
It was allowed to use no mask in green areas when a distance of 3m is ensured to others.
Leaving the municipality was disallowed unless for work, health care services, necessary care for a close relative, or funerals.
Restrictions to movement between municipalities were lifted.
Curfew hours were 10 PM to 5 AM.
Face masks were no longer obligatory outdoors if a distance to other is respected.
The curfew ended.
On 12 March, the first municipalities were put under quarantine, but people could still go out within their municipality.

A nationwide stay-at-home order was imposed: Public space may only be used individually for: purchasing food, necessary pharmaceutical products, and other essential products, assisting health facilities, going to work, returning home, assistance to elderly, minors, dependent persons, handicapped persons or other vulnerable persons, financial and insurance services, for emergencies or higher force. Children were allowed to accompany their parents in carrying out the allowed tasks.
From 30 March to 9 April, leaving to work was only allowed for workers in sectors that were seen as essential.
As of 26 April, children under 14 were allowed to go for a 1 hour walk with an adult within a radius of 1 km from home in the time between 9 AM and 9 PM.

From 2 May, people living in municipalities with fewer than 5000 inhabitants and with a small population density were allowed to go for a walk with one co-habitant and do sports alone once a day within 5 km from home, and keeping a distance toward others. People living in municipalities with over 5,000 inhabitants may go for a walk or do sports once a day as well, but only within 1 km from home and they had to follow a timetable: Non-institutionalised people over 70 and dependent people could go out between 10 AM to noon and 7 PM to 8 PM, people between 14 and 70 can go out from 6 AM to 10 AM and from 8 PM to 11 PM. Children could go out between noon and 7 PM (max. 3 children with one adult).

The further deescalation strategy differentiated between regions depending on the local incidence. In phase 1, gatherings of up to 10 persons were allowed, but the timetables for going out remained. It is unclear whether movement was still restricted to 1 km. On the one hand, this restriction was not lifted, on the other hand, it was allowed to move with a group of up to 10 persons within the province/island/sanitary division. Because it was not explicitly lifted, I assume that the 1 km rule could still be enforced in phase 1 even though it probably wasn't at most places. On 4 May, the first islands passed to phase 1.

The islands that first passed to phase 1, passed to phase 2. Movement was allowed In phase 2, for people under 70, going out was allowed at all times except between 10 AM and noon and between 7 PM and 8 PM. At these two time slots, only people over 70 were allowed to go out.
Since 21 May, face masks are mandatory everywhere where a distance of 2m to others cannot be maintained.
The first municipalities (islands of Formentera, El Hierro, La Gomera, and La Graciosa) entered phase 3 of the deescalation regime. This means, that freedom of movement was restored there.
On 8 June, large parts of the country moved to phase 3.
All provinces, including Madrid and four others that were still in phase 2, entered the last phase of deconfinement called ""new normality"".
Four municipalities in Aragon were moved back to phase 2 with limitations to movement as described above.

Catalunya made wearing face masks in open public spaces mandatory no matter the distance. In the following weeks, many other provinces followed (Catalonia, Extremadura, Balearic Islands, Murcia, Andalusia, Aragon, La Rioja, Navarra, Asturias, Castile Leon, Basque Country, Castile-La Mancha, Valencia, Galicia, Madrid, Canary Islands)
Freedom of movement was restored in the four municipalities closed on 22 June.
37 neighborhoods in Madrid were put under a confinement policy. Entering or leaving these zones is only allowed with reasons related to work, studies, important errands, or for helping those in need.
Now freedom of movement was restored within municipalities, but it remained not allowed to leave or enter 10 municipalities in the region of madrid including the capital.
A court suspended the rules on not leaving certain municipalities in Madrid.

With the new national state of alarm, a curfew from 11 PM to 6 AM was imposed. Regional authorities may shift start and end of the curfew by up to one hour. The curfew was not imposed on the Canary islands. It was not allowed to leave the municipality or city of residence in the entire country.
The curfew was since then also imposed on the Canary Islands.

Masks had to be worn in all public places, inside and outside, no matter the distance. In most provinces, this rule was in place before, but under previous legislation, which few provinces left unchanged, masks had only to be worn outside if a minimum distance toward others was not maintained.

The national curfew was lifted. In four provinces (Canarias, Navarra, Baleares, and La Comunidad Valenciana), it was initially kept in place. But on the Canary Islands, this decision was overturned by the provincial court so that the curfew had to be lifted. On the Balearic islands, the judges have ruled that the curfew may remain in place. The ban on leaving the municipality / sanitary area remained in several provinces. The curfew in the Comunidad Valenciana was shortened to midnight to 6 AM, the one on the Balearic islands was 11 PM to 6 AM.
A court suspended the curfew in Navarra.
The curfew in the Comunidad Valenciana is prolonged, but curfew hours are shortened to 1 AM to 6 AM.
The curfew on the Balearic islands was ended.

The curfew in the Comunidad Valenciana was ended. Also, in the province, masks no longer had to be worn on beaches or in natural areas.
All provinces dropped restrictions of movements outside the municipality.
Masks are no longer mandatory outdoors, outside of gatherings wihout dless than 1.5 m distance

Sweden has never imposed any stay-at-home orders, curfews, or outside mask mandates. A general ban on movement would be unconstitional.  Sweden is also one of the few places with no mask mandates at all, there have been only temporary recommendations to wear them in public transport during rush hour and local recommendations for some other situations.
The strictest restrictions in Sweden banned public gatherings of more than 8 persons.

In the Canton Uri, people 65 or older must stay home with the exceptions of medical visits after prior phonecall, funerals of close relative, and essential work in the health sector. Going for shopping is not allowed, but going for a walk for maximally 2 hours a day, alone or with one other person was.

On 20 March, the stay-at-home order for older people was lifted again after the federal government stated that it is not allowed for the canton to impose such an order.
Nationally, all gatherings of more than 5 people were banned on that day. During the second wave, gatherings of up to 5 people remained allowed, too.

Before, masks were only mandatory in indoor settings. From this day on, masks have been made mandatory in some busy shopping streets as well when stores are open.
There were no nationwide stay-at-home orders, curfews or further outside mask mandates in Switzerland. Gatherings/meetings were restricted to not more than 5 people for several months.
No masks were required in outside areas anymore. Before, masks had been mandatory at daytime in some busy streets.
People aged 65 or older and people who suffer chronic illnesses were restricted to leave their home and to walk in open areas such as parks or gardens.
Several villages were put under quarantine, not allowing any entrance or exit to/from these villages.
On 30 March, a total of 39 residential areas was under quarantine.
On April 3, the stay-at-home order was extended to young people under 20 years of age.
A weekend curfew was introduced in 31 provinces. This included the weekends 11 and 12 April and 18 and 19 April.

change: On 10 May and on following Sundays, people over 65 were allowed to go out between 11 AM and 3 PM. They were allowed to go out only within walking distance from their home and wearing masks. Children under 14 were allowed the same on 13 May during the same hours and 15 to 20 year olds on 15 May. These age groups (young people and elderly) had to wear a mask at all times when outside. In 23 provinces, a general mask mandate was imposed. In the following weeks (unclear when exactly) the stay-at-home order was lifted for 18 to 20 years olds and those under 18 were allowed outside on Wednesdays for some hours.

change: Minors and persons over 65 were allowed outside between 10 AM and 8 PM. Minors were only allowed to go outside accompanied by at least one of their parents. I found no source that the restrictions for persons under 18 and over 65 were lifted in the next months.
During the university entrance exams, a curfew was imposed between 9.30 AM and 3 PM on 27 June and between 9.30 AM and 6.30 PM on 28 June.
The exam curfew ended.

On 5 August, it was announced that tourists over 65 are excempt from the curfew which was still in place from 8 PM to 10 AM for locals. On the other hand, those over 65 who don't have a residence permit but are not tourists must remain home.
Wearing a mask was made mandatory for all people in all public areas as from 8 September.
It was decided by Erzurum Governorship, that people over 65 were only allowed in the streets between 10 AM and 4 PM.

change: In all Turkish provinces, citizens 65 or older were only allowed to go out  between 10 AM and 1 PM and citizens under 20 between 1 PM and 4 PM. On weekends, a curfew for everyone was in place from 8 PM to 10 AM with the exception of foreign tourists.
On 24 November, seven villages were quarantined.

From 1 December, a curfew was imposed on weekdays as well, from 9 PM to 5 AM. Over the weekends the curfew lasted from 9 PM on Friday until 5 AM on Monday. Those 65 years or older are only allowed outside on weekdays between 10 AM and 1 PM, and those under 20 years old only on weekdays between 1 PM and 4 PM.
It was declared that the weekend curfew would end, but in fact it was imposed again on all subsequent weekends.
Against the former report, weekend curfews continued.

change: As of 29 April, a stricter lockdown was imposed that allowed no one to leave their house unless for essential shopping or urgent medical treatments. All travel between cities required offical approval.

The daytime stay-at-home order was ended. A night curfew remained from 9 PM to 5 AM. Also, weekend curfews were reintroduced, from Friday 9 PM to Monday 5 AM. Citizens over the age of 65 who weren’t vaccinated are only allowed out on weekdays between 10 AM and 2 PM. Everyone over 65 and under 18 may not use public transport. A travel permit was no longer needed for inter-city travel.

Curfew times were shortened. Curfew now applies from Monday to Saturday between 10 PM and 5 AM and between Saturday 10 PM and Monday 5 AM. Restrictions on old people and minors remained mostly the same, but unvaccinated people over 65 were allowed from Monday to Saturday between 10 AM and 2 PM now.
The curfew was announced to be lifted from 1 July.
Commercial intercity road travel was banned, but private travel was allowed. Already the day before, the metro in Kyiv, Kharkiv and Dnipro stopped operating

People over 60 years of age were only allowed to go outside within 2 km from their home to make essential purchases. From 6 April, a mask had to be worn in all public places. This did not cover all streets, but e.g. in Kiew, a mask had to be worn within 50 m of every bus station. Also, it was banned to be outside without an ID and going to public parks, squares, recreation areas, forest parks, and coastal areas was banned, except for walking a pet. Many public places were closed for the public, including squares. Not more than 2 persons were allowed to be together in public space.
From 11 May, parks, squares etc. were made open for the public again.
The stay-at-home order for people over 60 was no longer mandatory.
As of 23 March 2021, in ""red zones"" (regions with a relatively high incidence), wearing masks outside was made mandatory. There were exceptions for parks and gardens.

The government issued a guidance that mandates people to stay home. It is not clear to me whether this guidance was already legally binding, but the language used indicates so. 
Yet, the actual legal regulations seem to have come into force some days later (see below).
It was only allowed to leave the house for ""reasonable excuses"" These included, but were not limited to: Exercise (alone or with one other member of the household), essential work that cannot be done from home, essential purchases, medical needs or providing care for others. Gatherings of more than two people were banned. However, there was a lot of confusion about the permit to leave the house for exercise. According to the Prime Minister, NHS website, and several media reports, it was only allowed to exercise once a day. This was not indicated in the English, Scottish or Northern Irish law, however. In the Welsh law, it was indeed indicated that people were only allowed to exercise once a day.
Vulnerable persons were asked to ""shield"", i.e. to completely stay at home and isolate themselves. This was not a compulsory measure though. BBC wrote of people ""being allowed"" to go outside in May however after they ""should"" have shielded, so even though shielding was never legally required, authoritarian language was used in public communication.
The legally binding regulations for the stay-at-home order came into force in England and Wales.
The regulations came into force in Scotland.
On 28 March, the lockdown came into force in Northern Ireland bringing it in line with the rest of the UK.

BBC reported of published police guidelines explaining what counts as a ""reasonable excuse"" to be outside and what doesn't. For instance, it was clarified that a short break during a long walk was okay, but ""A very short period of 'exercise' to excuse a long period of inactivity may mean that the person is not engaged in 'exercise' but in fact something else,""

While before it was just a crime to leave the house, from 22 April it was changed in England to being outside the house so that people could not e.g. leave the house to go to the supermarket but then stay outside to have a picnic afterwards. Similar changes happened in the other parts of the UK.

Apparently, in Guernsey, there was a limit of spending a maximum of two hours outdoors for exercise or recreational activities as it was announced on 5 May that this time will be extended to four hours. Similarly, on Jersey it was announced on 2 May, that it was allowed to spend 4 hours outside the home (not just exercise). Jersey and Guernsey are not part of the UK, but are dependencies of the british crown.

In Wales and in Scotland, from 11 May, it was also declared that it was allowed to exercise more than once a day (even though the law never restricted it in Scotland), but picnics or sunbathing were not allowed. In Wales, it was also clarified not to travel ""a significant distance"" from home.

In England, from 13 May, it was allowed  to take unlimited exercise and to enjoy parks and public spaces without exercising (to visit a public open space for the purposes of open-air recreation to promote their physical or mental health or emotional wellbeing) alone, with persons from the same household or with one person from another household. The general advice changed from ""stay home"" to ""stay alert"".
In Scotland, it was on 29 May, that ""outdoor recreation"" was allowed as a ""reasonable excuse"".

In England, restrictions on leaving the house or being outside of the house were lifted. It was now only restricted to stay somewhere else overnight. In Wales, the restrictions on leaving the house were lifted as well. It was not allowed to leave the area local to the place of living except for some reasons. This included exercising when the exercise started and ended at the place of living. Restrictions for risk groups to “shield” (which apparently were not legally binding) were also lifted.
From this day, people advised to “shield” in Northern Ireland were “allowed” to go out again. Yet I found no indication that they were indeed legally banned to go out.
The Scottish government replaced their ""stay home"" message with a ""stay safe"" message, but the formal restrictions on movement remained.
In Scotland, restrictions on leaving the house or being outside of the house were lifted.
In Northern Ireland, restrictions on leaving the house or being outside of the house were lifted.
In Wales, restrictions on leaving the municipality were imposed on several municipalities over the next weeks.

Another stay-at-home order was imposed in Wales. Exercise counted as a ""reasonable excuse"" to leave from home. The bans on leaving local boundaries had ended, but people were asked not to drive significant distances, e.g. to reach the mountains.

In Scotland, a 5 tier ""lockdown"" was imposed from 2 November which allegedly included the ban on leaving the district in tiers 3 and 4, but despite the goverment urging people to follow these rules, they were not legally binding.
In England, a stay-at-home order was imposed from 5 November. Leaving the house was bound to ""reasonable excuses"" again, including unlimited exercise.
The lockdown in Wales ended.
Scotland introduced travel restrictions. People living tier 3 or tier 4 areas must remain within their county boundaries unless they have a “reasonable excuse” for leaving.
The lockdown in England ended.

A new stay-at-home order was imposed on Wales. Exercise was allowed but had to start and end at the place of residence.
Also as of 21 December, a new ""tier-four"" was imposed on large parts of England including the entire South East and London. Rules on meeting people were relaxed slightly only for Christmas day. Under tier four, people had to stay in their area. But within the area,it was allowed to go for unlimited exercise. There was no clear guidance on what constituted remaining in ""their local area"" thus there have been disagreements in some cases.

Northern Ireland entered a new lockdown on 26 December supposedly including a stay-at-home order, also allowed for exercise. But again, this order seems not to have been written in law at that time, but was only legalised on 8 January. Outdoor exercise remained allowed with one member of another household. Most of Scotland (with the exception of some islands) entered a new lockdown on 26 December, but did not impose a formal stay-at-home order. Leaving the municipality was only allowed for ""essential reasons"" however.
On 31 December, the majority (44 million) of English people were under tier four.

As of 5 January 2021, a stay-at-home order was imposed on Scotland as well with the exception of islands. Among the accepted reasons for leaving the house is to ""undertake exercise or recreation"" outdoors that starts and ends at the same place which must be in the local government area in which the person lives or within 5 miles of this area, and was either undertaken alone with members of the household or in the form of another allowed gathering.
From 6 January, all of England was put under tier four with strictened rules. Leaving the house was allowed only for certain reasons, including exercise.

Northern Ireland entered a new lockdown on 26 December supposedly including a stay-at-home order, also allowed for exercise. But again, this order seems not to have been written in law at that time, but was only legalised on 8 January. Outdoor exercise remained allowed with one member of another household.
The Scottish Islands of Barra and Vatersay were put under level 4 restrictions (including a stay-at-home order) from 20 January.
All Scotish Western Isles were put under level 4 restrictions (including a stay-at-home order) from 29 January (these moved back to level 3 on 24 March).
From 13 March, Wales was the first part of the UK to replace the stay-at-home order with a stay-local order.
The ""stay local"" mandate in Wales was lifted.

The stay-at-home order in England was lifted and replaced with a “stay local” rule, that was, however, not enshrined in legally binding regulations. Overnight stays outside of one’s area (e.g. village or part of city) continued to be banned.
The stay-at-home order in Scotland was lifted on 2 April as it was replaced by a ban on leaving the local authority boundaries without an essential reason.
Northern Ireland was the last of the four countries of the UK to lift its stay-at-home order. It was replaced with a “stay local” messaging with overnight stays away from home still banned.
On 16 April, internal travel across Scotland (with the exception of overnight stays) was allowed again.
Free travel between the different parts of the United Kingdom was restored
